postcontent:
Price: $300

Technical Details / Condition: 

For sale is a Mauser Model 1910 pocket pistol in 25ACP. Marked 'Waffenfabrik Mauser A.S. Obendorf A.N. Mauser Patent' with Mauser Stamp on frame and on original grips. All numbered parts are matching with serial number #80xxx placing production date between 1914 and 1921. Magazine is original but unnumbered. Bore is worn but sufficiently rifled still. Finish is worn on lower aspect of frame but overall okay, looks like holster wear. Grips are original. I believe this is a transitional model 1910/1914 as per page 3 of http://www.mauserguns.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/Mauser1910.pdf. 

Additional Information:

Although still a pocket gun, it is larger than most 25acp handguns which was very helpful shooting at the range. The gun functions well but did not like aluminum cased ammo (at least in my experience). Accuracy was comparable to a .38 snub nose in my hands, about what I expected from it so I think in better hands it would group well.  No military or other markings save the proof mark and Mauser banner and writing mentioned above. Was a fun range toy but I have moved on to more fun german guns.

I have a Remsport , out of Ludlow Ma., Commander build, the frame is a serialized forged lower in Stainless Steel, 25LPI checkered front strap, frame tangs are roughed for a beavertail grip safety.

I fired it on a Colt officer frame I have and it worked flawless. The front of the slide has a chip in the cerakote so it will need to be recoated at some point. I had the slide fitted recently to the frame by pistol smith Greg Derr, Derr Precision in Marshfield, Ma., it slides like butter on a hot skillet. 

8/25/14 ... I just ordered over $400 in parts to finish this build, the price will obviously go up. Greg Derr has the pistol again and is fitting a Beavetail Grip safety, flush cutting the barrel/doing a small crown, tweaking the a Wilson extended thumb safety to better fit the frame contour and fitting a Greider trigger to the frame. I ordered mostly Ed Brown Parts, fire control, thumb safety and springs, and a Wilson ext. slide stop like the one in the picture except in SS.  I'm going to have the cerakote stripped off the slide , coating choice is still in the air.

The parts are in , I will finish the gun to the buyers liking depending on the $

  I have over $1500 into this project. Remsport is a supplier for some of the HIGH END 1911 makers. After some digging the ONLY high end maker that I could find that sold 25lpi checkered parts is ED BROWN, so this may be the same frame and slide assembly as what they use???

My loss your gain

postcontent:
I have this Iver Johnson top break revolver that needs a new home. It is a double tower small frame 4" barrel in .32 Smith & Wesson. It is a "third generation" or "third model", with a serial number of J6015. The third model safety hammer "J" prefixes were manufactured from 1927 through 1940, though I haven't done the research to find out exactly what year this one was made. It does not fit my hand well at all, which is why I'm selling it. The bluing has definitely seen better days, but it functions quite well for its age. I fired 11 rounds through it, and had one problem. One round was a "light strike". I'm certainly no gunsmith, but I think it has a little too much play in the top latch, resulting in a hair too much distance between the firing pin and the primer of the cartridge. Maybe you can fix this, but I know I don't want to try. I just fire 'em. The cylinder timing works perfect, and the ejector works great as well. It comes with a box of Magtech ammo, 39 rounds left.
